A longer toe finger than ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men whose toe finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously less likely to suffer from prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published by the British Journal of Cancer on Wednesday.
This should be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, and this in particular in men up to sixty," said the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, Professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially when genetic risks or other risk factors are present, such as family health risks, added Mrs Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, she followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer with her colleagues in Britain, but also 3000 healthy men.
With more than half of the participants in the study, the toy finger was shorter in the right hand than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer was true, as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and toy fingers were equal in length.
In men whose toe finger was longer than the ring finger, however, this risk fell by 33 percent, in men up to sixty-eight percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned, which are already in prenatal age, clearly reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research showed that the testosterone is accelerating the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, said ČTK that this study was fleetingly known to him, yet he did not consider the relationship between finger length and cancer risk to be "fully proven".
