Sports and regulation
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventive spirit, but not the will to bypass a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 game against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed on whether it was an unsportal act or not, and whether the two players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is generally known, the two players lost a few minutes before playing (their team had already gained clearly) time and played several fouls so that the arbitrator showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead his group, the two players will meet the required sanctions in the next match against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game without any cards.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee punished the coach of the club, José Mourinho, with two games and the participating players with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the Ethos - the unwritten, but followed by the rules in this sport.
Part of the upcoming debate about the case presented is that a team of the Real Madrid football club (who in his Hymne offers noble courage and honour and on other occasions had punished his players for similar incidents) played the main role, and on the dramatization by Mourinho, who has added an episode more to his long history than theatrician and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate focuses on whether or not it does not expressly contradict the principles of sport, i.e. whether these acts constitute a regular outline. In fact, this procedure adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to ignore its sense.
In this case, the damage caused by the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not threatened by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to prevent the opposing players from taking unfair advantage of the counter-team. Nor did it.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand under misplay or regular bypass, because the circumvention of the rule has not been carried out secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as striking as possible for it to be punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the opponents drew from the intentional fouls.
It should be stressed here that the rival was not brought into an unfavorable situation nor that advantages were attached to the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next season of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term advantage, up to a certain degree of uncertain advantage, as the team might eventually leave out. Furthermore, players receive a sanction with this procedure and pass into the second card cycle, in which they leave with a card less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
This does not make it so clear whether it really is an advantage.
Finally, such practices are not directed against the sports spirit, which also includes strategic decisions, in order to derive maximum benefit from the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to avoid sanctions (that would actually be a clear case of regular circumvention), they wanted to choose when they submitted to them.
They made a strategic decision not to avoid or flee from punishment.
Although the boundary between the inventiveness and the regular environment is blurry, I believe that this is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemics were caused by two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the type of provocative control transfer.
The damage caused by these actions by the principles of sport is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
