China maintains its greenhouse gas reduction targets
The representative of China stated at COP16 that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon trace levels and it would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China considers its offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, assures Su Wei, the representative of this country at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th World Climate Summit of the United Nations (COP16), Su Wei assured that his country would have made enormous efforts to reduce carbon traces and transform its industry.
He stated that in the last four years his country has invested 245 million dollars to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its objectives but would work on this matter together with the international community.
He stated that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institutions building and support for pilot programmes.
In all aspects, progress has been made, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which included the objectives of reducing gas emissions, he stated.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China the authorities of the states had cooperated with those of the Central State and the municipalities in order to achieve the energy saving targets, effective use of energy and reduction of emissions.
In addition, he explained that several multiannual plans have already been launched or concluded, both those financed by the Chinese Government and those receiving funds from other countries.
For example, he referred to the programme for the effective use of energy, which has been introduced over the past five years and which has received investments from the United Nations (UNO), the government and from private hands.
There is also a project at the provincial level on climate change, another to exchange traditional bulbs through energy savings and another to weaken and adapt, he explained.
Martin Krol, a scientific government consultant on climate change in this country, confirmed that China's efforts would be far greater than generally accepted.
It showed that the per capita emissions of greenhouse gases in China amounted to six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tonnes. China is responsible for a nine percent overall contribution to the pollution.
Similarly, there has been unprecedented progress in the field of energy use, and energy efficiency has been increased by 20 percent over the past five years and a further move is due to take place by 2020.
