According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of the FCKW issued on earth due to lighting, if the white-gliding pears, which until now still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or better, by light diodes (LED).
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the worldwide fleet exhaust gases.
Last year in Copenhagen, the major exhaust gas issuers, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to reduce the global FFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, this balance sheet would have to be reduced by 5 gt to stabilise the increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today until 2020 to prevent it from being out of control.
In the white glowing pears 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact light bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED bulbs reducing this energy demand by twice.
