Several specialists have indicated that compact light bulbs have reserves, as they contain mercury, and that it is therefore necessary to dispose of them as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except for producers to provide an acceptance site.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact light bulb, but rather the coal power plants that emit much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-flooding pears.
In the United States alone, these coal power plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury annually.
